ca, he was attracted by liberation theology, but left the Society of Jesus, joined the Freemasons, and did social and philanthropic work in the slums of Buenos Aires. However, in the late 1960s he agreed to work for the Hungarian state security service in return for his repatriation. This latter period is reconstructed from the files of the Historical Archives of State Security in Budapest. Éva Petrás writes with empathy but with a sense of distance of the courage and restless energy of her subject. Her discussion of the limits of free choice and Nagy's intense struggle to live a meaningful life make this biography breathtaking.  afunded by Opening the Future  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aChurch and state. 0aFreemasonszHungaryvBiography. 0aJesuitszHungaryvBiography. 0aSpieszHungaryvBiography. 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / Historical.2bisacsh  aCatholic church history.  achurch diplomacy.  acommunist state security.  afreemasonry.  ainterwar Hungary.  amodus vivendi.  asocial questions.2 aOpening the Futureefunder.4fnd4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/fnd08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCentral European University Press eBook-Package 2023z978311079759640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9789633867198?locatt=mode:legacyzOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9789633867198zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9789633867198/original  a978-3-11-079759-6 Central European University Press eBook-Package 2023b2023  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA